        And I compare that life to the past weeks here — creative rebuilding, individual voices, genuine connections, being valued for what I uniquely contribute.

        The absurdist irony isn't lost on me — bureaucratic alien plants somehow created more authentic community than human bureaucracy ever did.

        Scout bounces a question to me — "I okay?"

        I tell them, "I'm figuring something out."

        The human freighter will arrive in two days — forty-eight hours to decide.

        But honestly? — I think I already know.

        I just need to be sure — to examine it from every angle, talk to everyone, understand what staying means and what leaving means.

        Because this isn't just about where I physically exist.

        It's about where I belong.

        And belonging — real belonging — is rarer than I ever understood.

        Scout curls up against me — waiting, supportive, loyal no matter what.

        The facility hums with quiet activity: Runner's underground network creating subtle harmonics, Velvet's growth providing a comfortable structure, Remedy's enhancement compounds making the air pleasant, Holloway's bioluminescence illuminating shared spaces, Florence's tactical designs keeping everyone safe, Scout's affection holding us together.

        Individual voices creating collective harmony.

        And somewhere in that harmony, I found my voice too.

        Two days to decide — but the decision is crystallizing with every moment I spend examining it.

        ¶

        Home isn't where you're from — home is where your _voice matters_.
